Dog Hiking Safety", "\u2022 Provide your dog with year-round protection from fleas and \u2022 Hiking on a trail with other dogs, wildlife and people can be very", "ticks. Use a safe topical medication once a month or as exciting and distracting for you and your dog. Your dog should", "advised by your veterinarian. It can take up to 24 hours for the have basic obedience training so that he or she can walk on a", "medication to fully absorb; for large dogs, you may want to loose leash.", "put the medication on several places along his or her spine for", "\u2022 Dogs can overheat very quickly since they do not sweat. faster absorption.", "Remember to give your dog water and a chance to cool down.", "\u2022 Be polite on the trail to other fellow hikers. Pull you dog to the Temperatures can rise quickly as you hike up the trail, due to", "side when passing other hikers. Always let horses and cyclists the lack of shade and water. Dogs can only cool themselves off", "pass you first. by panting, so if the air is hot and they are dehydrated, they can", "easily get heat exhaustion.", "\u2022 Always ask a dog owner first if your dog wants to meet an", "approaching dog. Not everyone will be ready to meet a strange \u2022 Make sure the ground temperature isn\u2019t too hot that it burns", "dog; asking first and walking up slowly to the other dog usually your dog\u2019s paws.", "allows for a friendly greeting!", "\u2022 Stay on the trail for your dog\u2019s safety as well as yours and", "watch for dangerous wildlife including rattlesnakes, scorpions,", "coyotes, mountain lions, and even bears in some locations.", "\ufffd \ufffd Dog tags on your dog\u2019s collar Enough water for you and your dog", "with a container for her to use", "\ufffd One tag with your contact", "\ufffd information Tick removal tool (available at most", "pet stores)", "What", "\ufffd Your dog\u2019s current rabies license tag", "\ufffd Sunscreen for your dog if he or she", "\ufffd Poop bag(s) to scoop up the